        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is .htaccess Redirect Malware?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Your .htaccess file is a powerful configuration file located in the root directory. When hackers compromise a site, they inject malicious rules into this file to intercept incoming visitors and immediately redirect them to spam or malicious websites."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "If my site is infected, why can I still access it normally?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Hackers use 'conditional redirects' to avoid detection. The malware checks your User-Agent and Referer. It often only redirects visitors coming from search engines (Google, Bing) or using mobile devices, while showing the normal site to the admin."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Why does the malware come back after I delete it?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "The modified .htaccess file is just a symptom. The root cause is a hidden 'dropper' or 'regenerator' script (a PHP file) located elsewhere on your server. This script runs periodically to check if the .htaccess file is clean and re-injects the malware."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How do I fix .htaccess redirect malware permanently?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "1. Access your server via FTP and remove the malicious code from .htaccess. 2. Change file permissions to 444 (read-only). 3. Use a security plugin like Wordfence to hunt for the hidden dropper script. 4. Check for malicious Cron Jobs."
